Program Intention :
===============================================================================================
The call to memcpy() returns a pointer to the next byte in dst after c , or NULL if c 
was not found.
memcpy() is used to copy a block of memory from one location to another. It is declared 
in <string.h> header file.

===============================================================================================
COMPILE :

linux@linux:~/Linux_programming/Chapter7_Memory_Management/pg290_memcpy$ make
gcc -Wall -g -o pg290_memcpy pg290_memcpy.c;

===============================================================================================
Execution:

linux@linux:~/Linux_programming/Chapter7_Memory_Management/pg290_memcpy$ ./pg290_memcpy
Before memcpy dest = the same!!
After memcpy dest = function behaves
linux@linux:~/Linux_programming/Chapter7_Memory_Management/pg290_memcpy$

===============================================================================================
Program Flow
===============================================================================================
	void * memcpy (void *dst, const void *src, size_t n);
	It copies “src” bytes from address “dst” to address “to”.
	It returns a pointer to the memory location where data is copied.




